"Android is exploring more private ways for apps to show you ads"
"The new privacy features in the Privacy Sandbox let apps show you relevant ads, but restrict what those apps can learn about your activities on websites and apps from other developers."
"Turning on the beta allows apps to test these new, more private ways to show you ads. You can turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."
"You’re part of Android’s ads privacy beta. The Privacy Sandbox is turned on for your device.\n\nYou can learn more or turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."
"Thank you for your response. The Privacy Sandbox is turned off for your device.\n\nIf you change your mind or want to learn more, go to your privacy settings."
"The Privacy Sandbox is on for your device, and apps can test these new, more private ways to show you ads. You can turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."

"Android’s Privacy Sandbox provides new features that apps can use to show you ads that you might like. These technologies don’t use device identifiers.\n\nAndroid and your apps can estimate the kind of ads that you might be interested in, and save the interests temporarily on your device. This allows apps to show you ads that you might like, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."

"Android periodically estimates your top interests based on the apps that you use, for example, 'Sports' or 'Travel'.

Later, an app can ask Android to use these interests to show you more relevant ads.

You can see the list of current interests in your privacy settings, and block any that you don’t like."

"Apps can estimate your interests and temporarily save these with Android. For example, an app that you use to buy running shoes might estimate your interest as 'running marathons'.

Later, based on this interest, a different app can show you an ad related to marathons.

In your privacy settings, you can manage the list of apps that have saved interests."
"Ad topics and new controls give you more choice over the ads that you see"

"Android notes topics of interest based on apps that you’ve used recently. Also, apps that you use can determine what you like. Later, apps can ask for this information to show you personalised ads. You can choose which topics and apps are used to show you ads."
"To measure the performance of an ad, limited types of data are shared between apps."
"Apps can ask Android for information to help personalise the ads that you see."
"• Android notes topics of interest based on the apps that you’ve used recently."

"• Apps that you use can also determine what you like based on how you use them. For example, if you use an app that sells long-distance running shoes, the app might decide that you’re interested in running marathons."
"Later, an app you use can ask for this information – either your ad topics or ads suggested by apps that you’ve used."
"Android auto-deletes topics and app-suggested data regularly. You can also block specific topics and apps that you don’t want to make suggestions."
"Apps that you use can ask Android for information to help them measure the performance of their ads. Android lets apps collect limited types of data, such as the time of day an ad was shown to you."
"Ad topics give you more choice over the ads that you see"
"Android is launching new privacy features that give you more choice over the ads that you see."

"Ad topics help apps show you relevant ads while protecting your identity and information about your app usage. Android can note topics of interest based on the apps that you’ve used recently. Later, an app you use can ask Android for relevant topics to personalise the ads that you see."
"You can see ad topics in your device settings and block the ones that you don’t want shared with apps. Android also auto-deletes ad topics regularly."
"You can change your mind at any time in privacy settings."
"Learn more about how Android protects your data in our ""privacy policy""."
"Your ad topics are based on the apps that you’ve used recently on this device and how frequently you use them."

"Android notes topics of interest as you use your apps. Topic labels are predefined and include things like Arts & entertainment, Shopping and Sports. Later, an app that you use can ask Android for a few of your topics (but not data about your app usage or identity) to personalise the ads you see."
"• How you can manage your data"

"Android auto-deletes topics regularly. As you continue using apps, a topic might reappear on the list. You can also block topics that you don’t want Android to share with apps, and turn ad topics off at any time in privacy settings."
"You can make changes in privacy settings."
"Android also offers new ways to limit what apps can learn about you when they show you personalised ads."

"• App-suggested ads help protect your identity and information about your app usage while enabling apps to show you relevant ads. Based on your activity, an app that you use can suggest related ads on other apps. You can see a list of apps and block them from making suggestions, in privacy settings."
"• With ad measurement, limited types of data are shared between apps to measure the performance of their ads, such as the time of day that an ad was shown to you."
"More about app-suggested ads and ad measurement"
"Your activity in an app that you use on this device."

"Apps can store information with Android about things that you like. For example, if you use an app about marathon training, the app might decide that you’re interested in running shoes. Later, if you use a different app, that app can show you an ad for running shoes suggested by the first app."
"• How you can manage your data"
"Android auto-deletes app-suggested data regularly. An app that you use again might reappear on the list."
"You can also block an app from suggesting ads for you, reset all ad-suggestion data or turn app-suggested ads off at any time in privacy settings."
"Apps that you use can ask Android for information that helps them measure the performance of their ads. Android protects your privacy by limiting the information apps can share with one another."
"Have more choice over the ads that you see while still protecting your identity"
"Android is launching new ways to limit what apps can learn about you when they show you personalised ads."

"• With app-suggested ads, new privacy features help to protect your identity and information about your app usage, while enabling apps to show you relevant ads. Based on your activity, an app that you use can suggest related ads on other apps. You can see a list of apps and block them from making suggestions in privacy settings."
"• With ad measurement, limited types of data are shared between apps to understand the performance of their ads, such as the time of day that an ad was shown to you."
"Your activity in an app on this device may be used to suggest ads."
"Android also offers a new privacy feature that gives you more choice over the ads you see."

"Ad topics help apps show you relevant ads while protecting your identity and information about your app usage. Android can note topics of interest based on the apps that you\'ve used recently. Later, an app that you use can ask Android for relevant topics to show you more relevant ads."
"You can see ad topics in your privacy settings and block the ones that you don\'t want to be shared with apps. Android also auto-deletes ad topics regularly."
"Now, you have more choice over the ads that you see while still protecting your identity"
"Android now offers new privacy features that give you more choice over the ads you see."

"Apps can use the Privacy Sandbox to measure the effectiveness of their ads. To do this, advertisers can temporarily save data with Android about your interactions between their ads and apps. The amount of data that they can save is restricted and will be deleted regularly.\n\nYou can delete this data at any time by turning off the Privacy Sandbox."

"Android periodically estimates your top interests based on the apps that you use. Apps can ask Android to use these interests to show you more relevant ads.\n\nIf you block an interest, it won’t be added to the list again unless you unblock it. You may still see some related ads."
"No topics to show at the moment.\nLearn more about ""ad topics"

"Android’s ads privacy beta provides new features that apps can use to show you ads that you might like. These technologies don’t use device identifiers.\n\nAndroid can estimate the kind of ads that you might be interested in and save these interests temporarily on your device. This allows apps to show you relevant ads, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."

"Apps can estimate your interests and temporarily save these with Android. Later, a different app can show you an ad based on these interests.\n\nIf you block an app, it won’t estimate any more interests. It won’t be added to this list of apps again unless you unblock it. Interests already estimated by the app will be deleted, but you might still see some related ads."
"No apps are generating interests for you at the moment"
"No apps to show at the moment. \nLearn more about ""app-suggested ads"

"Android’s ads privacy beta provides new features that apps can use to show you ads that you might like. These technologies don’t use device identifiers.\n\nApps can estimate the kind of ads that you might be interested in and save these interests temporarily on your device. This allows apps to show you relevant ads, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."
"Apps and advertisers can request information from Android that helps them measure the performance of their ads.\n\nAd measurement data is deleted regularly from your device."

"Android protects your privacy by limiting the information that apps can share with one another. Reports are sent with a delay to protect your identity.

Your browser may have a similar setting. If ads measurement is on for both Android and your browser, a company may be able to measure the effectiveness of an ad between apps that you use and sites that you visit. Your browsing history is kept private on your device.

Learn more about how Android protects your data in our ""privacy policy""."

"Apps that you use can also determine what you like based on how you use them."

"Topics of interest are based on the apps that you’ve used recently and are used by apps to show you personalised ads.\n\nYou can block topics that you don’t want shared with apps. Android also auto-deletes topics regularly."

"Android notes topics of interest based on the apps that you’ve used in the last few weeks.

Later, an app you use can ask Android for your topics to personalise the ads that you see. Android shares up to three topics while protecting your identity and information about your app usage.

Android auto-deletes topics regularly. As you continue using apps, a topic might reappear on the list. Or you can block topics that you don’t want Android to share with apps.

In your apps, an ad that you see may be personalised, depending on this setting, the app-suggested ads setting, your advertising ID settings and whether the app that you’re using personalises ads."
"Apps that you use can determine what you like and then suggest ads on other apps.\n\nYou can block apps from making suggestions. Android also auto-deletes app-suggested data regularly."

"It’s common for apps that you use to remember things that you’re interested in to personalise your experience. Apps can also store information with Android about your topics.

For example, if you use an app about marathon training, the app might decide that you’re interested in running shoes. Later, if you use a different app, that app can show you an ad for running shoes suggested by the first app.

Android auto-deletes app-suggested data regularly. An app you use again might reappear on the list. Or you can block an app from suggesting ads for you.

In your apps, an ad you see may be personalised, depending on this setting, the ad topics setting, your advertising ID settings and whether the app that you’re using personalises ads."
"Only very limited info is shared between apps to help measure ad performance"

"We\'re launching a new ads privacy feature called ads measurement. Android only shares very limited information between apps, such as when an ad was shown to you, to help apps measure the performance of ads."
"You can make changes in ads privacy settings."
"Apps that you use can ask Android for information to help them measure the performance of their ads. Android lets apps collect limited types of data only."
